The stock account rate of return compounds monthly, so; we will divide the rate over 12, which represents the number of months in a year. Hence we will express the rate using the following equation:

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Rate} &=\dfrac{0.10}{12}
\end{aligned}$$

Let's now calculate the future value of the stock investment.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Future Value of an Annuity} &=\$750\times\dfrac{\left(1+ \dfrac{0.10}{12}\right)^{360}-1}{\dfrac{0.10}{12}}\
\\[20pt]
 &=\$750\times\dfrac{19.83739937
-1}{0.008333333}
\\[10pt]
&= \boxed{\$1,695,365.94}
\end{aligned}$$

Hence, the future value of the stock investment after 30 years is $1,695,365.94.

The bond's rate of return compounds monthly hence we will express the rate in the following equation:

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Rate} &=\dfrac{0.06}{12}
\end{aligned}$$

Let's now determine the bond's future value.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Future Value of an Annuity} &=\$250\times\dfrac{\left(1+ \dfrac{0.06}{12}\right)^{360}-1}{\dfrac{0.06}{12}}\
\\[20pt]
 &=\$250\times\dfrac{6.022575212
-1}{0.5}
\\[10pt]
&= \boxed{\$251,128.76 }
\end{aligned}$$

Therefore the value of the bond account after 30 years is $251,128.76.

Next, considering our previous calculations, we will combine the bond and the stock's future value to determine our total earning from our investments after 30 years.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Total earnings} &= \text{Stock account's future value}+\text{Bond account's future value}

\end{aligned}$$
